---
// The thesis, as a short editorial passage. Sets Cire apart from both paper and
// generic e-invites before any feature is named.
---
<section class="px-6 py-24 md:py-32" aria-labelledby="promise-heading">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-[52rem] text-center" data-reveal>
    <p class="font-body text-gold mb-6 text-[0.72rem] tracking-[0.28em] uppercase">
      Why Cire
    </p>
    <h2
      id="promise-heading"
      class="font-display text-text text-[clamp(1.9rem,4.5vw,3rem)] leading-[1.2] font-light italic"
    >
      A wax seal you can send as a link.
    </h2>
    <p class="font-body text-text-muted mx-auto mt-7 max-w-[40rem] text-[1.05rem] leading-[1.8] font-light">
      There is a moment when a guest opens your invitation — and that moment should feel like
      something. Paper captures it beautifully, but it can&rsquo;t carry a map, a guest list, or an
      RSVP. The usual digital invites carry all of that, and somehow feel like a form.
    </p>
    <p class="font-body text-text mt-6 mx-auto max-w-[40rem] text-[1.05rem] leading-[1.8] font-light">
      Cire is the third thing: an invitation that unwraps like the real thing, greets each guest by
      name, and quietly does the work — counting every reply while your guests simply feel invited.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
